The following assumptions were made regarding the financial plan:
&nbsp;
* Predicted sales increase of 15\%
&nbsp;
* Predicted increase in the balance sheet accounts (asset) vary with sales.

Now, let us compute the increase in the sales:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Increase in Sales}&=\text{Sales}\times\text{Rate of Increase}\\[12pt]
&={\$38,000}\times{15\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$5,700}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The increase in the sales amounts to \$5,700.**

Now, let us compute the projected sales:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Sales}&=\text{Sales}+\text{Increase in Sales}\\[12pt]
&={\$38,000}+{\$5,700}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$43,700}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected sales is \$43,700.**

Now, let us compute the percentage of cost in proportion to the sales:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Percentage of Cost}&=\frac{\text{Cost}}{\text{Sales}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$32,600}{\$38,000}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.86}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{86\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The percentage of cost in proportion to the sales is 86\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected cost:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Cost}&=\text{Projected Sales}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$43,700}\times{86\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$37,582}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected cost is \$37,582.**

Now, let us compute the projected net income:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Net Income}&=\text{Projected Sales}-\text{Projected Cost}\\[12pt]
&={\$43,700}-{\$37,582}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$6,118}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected net income is \$6,118.**

Now, let us compute the percentage of cost in proportion to the sales:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Percentage of Asset}&=\frac{\text{Asset}}{\text{Sales}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$27,300}{\$38,000}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.72}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{72\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The percentage of asset in proportion to the sales is 72\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected assets:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Assets}&=\text{Sales}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$43,700}\times{72\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$31,464}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected assets is \$31,464.**

Now, let us compute the cash dividend:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Cash Dividend}&=\text{Net Income}\times\text{0.50}\\[12pt]
&={\$6,118}\times{0.50}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$3,059}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The cash dividend amounts to \$3,059.**

Now, let us compute the total debt and equity:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Total Debt and Equity}&=\text{Debt}+\text{Equity}+\text{Cash Dividend}\\[12pt]
&={\$6,700}+{\$20,600}+{\$3,059}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$30,359}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The total debt and equity amounts to \$30,359.**

Now, let us compute the total equity:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Total Equity}&=\text{Equity}+\text{Cash Dividend}+\text{Retained Earnigns}\\[12pt]
&={\$20,600}+{\$3,059}+{\$3,059}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$26,718}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The total equity amounts to \$26,718.**

To balance the total debt and equity and the total assets, we are to compute the total debt to be reported in the pro forma statements:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Total Debt}&=\text{Total Assets}-\text{Total Equity}\\[12pt]
&={\$31,464}-{\$26,718}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$4,746}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The total debt amounts to \$4,746.**
